default These standards are by no means new, we find them in liberalism in the 17C:
default… the only purpose for which power can be rightfully exercised over any member of a civilized community, against his will, is to prevent harm to others. His own good, either phy
defaultsical or moral, is not a sufficient warrant. He cannot rightfully be compelled to do or forbear because it will be better for him to do so … because, in the opinions of others, to do so would be wise, or even right. These are good reasons for remonstrating
default with him, or reasoning with him, or persuading him or entreating him, but not for compelling him, or visiting him with any evil, in case he do otherwise.
defaultfrom On Liberty, John Stuart Mill, 1859
defaultEchoes of these ideas are found in our present day views on 
defaulthuman rights, discrimination and justice.
default The New Zealand Government, when working on an active transport strategy, once stated that they had “shot ourselves in the foot” with the promotion of bicycle helmets.
